            <biogHist>
                <p>Mary MacQueen was the daughter of Reverend Allan MacQueen, minister in North
                    Uist, and Mary MacQueen née MacDonald. She lived in North Uist and never
                    married. She died in 1860 as a result of 18 months of paralisis. </p>
                <p>In 1877 Carmichael collected a story entitled 'Màiri Bhoidheach' about Mary, who
                    had a song composed for her by Alexander Stewart, school master at Baileanloch
                    North Uist. Mary 'took such a dislike to the man [Stewart] that she could never
                    bear to hear the song'.</p>
